{
    "publish_date": "2013-03-25T12:31:34.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT7M34S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "DR. .JAMES GRIME: So today we&#39;re\ngoing to talk about one", 
            "dur": "1.66", 
            "start": "0.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of the great unsolved problems\nin mathematics that went back", 
            "dur": "3.91", 
            "start": "2.3"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to the Ancient Greeks, thousands\nof years ago, which", 
            "dur": "3.5", 
            "start": "6.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "was eventually solved in 1882.", 
            "dur": "4.4", 
            "start": "9.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And the problem is called\nsquaring the circle.", 
            "dur": "2.94", 
            "start": "14.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you may have even heard of\nthe problem as a metaphor for", 
            "dur": "2.69", 
            "start": "17.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "something that&#39;s impossible\nto do.", 
            "dur": "2.31", 
            "start": "19.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The question is, can you make a\nsquare with the same area as", 
            "dur": "3.9", 
            "start": "22.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the circle?", 
            "dur": "1.53", 
            "start": "25.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now you have to understand\nthe rules.", 
            "dur": "2.19", 
            "start": "27.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In Ancient Greece they\ndidn&#39;t have algebra.", 
            "dur": "2.589", 
            "start": "29.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So they could only\nconstruct numbers", 
            "dur": "2.161", 
            "start": "32.259"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "using lines and circles.", 
            "dur": "2.56", 
            "start": "34.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you could only make things\nusing a straight edge--", 
            "dur": "2.95", 
            "start": "36.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "like a ruler, but not a\nmeasured ruler, just a", 
            "dur": "2.2", 
            "start": "39.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "straight edge--", 
            "dur": "1.12", 
            "start": "42.13"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and a compass.", 
            "dur": "1.25", 
            "start": "43.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So lines and circles,\nthose are the rules.", 
            "dur": "2.79", 
            "start": "44.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Those are the rules the Ancient\nGreeks had to work by.", 
            "dur": "3.01", 
            "start": "47.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Using those rules, can you\nconstruct a square with the", 
            "dur": "4.54", 
            "start": "50.3"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "same area as the circle?", 
            "dur": "2.16", 
            "start": "54.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s have a look at\nwhat you can do", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with rules and compasses.", 
            "dur": "2.67", 
            "start": "58.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can add numbers.", 
            "dur": "0.59", 
            "start": "61.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Here&#39;s a line, and\nit has length a.", 
            "dur": "2.62", 
            "start": "61.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And I add another line\nof length b.", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "64.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And the whole thing\nis a plus b.", 
            "dur": "3.81", 
            "start": "67.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you can add numbers together", 
            "dur": "1.48", 
            "start": "71.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "quite easily with lines.", 
            "dur": "1.99", 
            "start": "72.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can subtract numbers,\nas well.", 
            "dur": "1.87", 
            "start": "74.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I start with b, and then I\nmark off a length, which I&#39;m", 
            "dur": "4.1", 
            "start": "76.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "going to call a, then this\nbit here, that&#39;s going", 
            "dur": "3.46", 
            "start": "80.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to be b minus a.", 
            "dur": "2.09", 
            "start": "84.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We can multiply.", 
            "dur": "1.24", 
            "start": "86.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I draw a little triangle\nhere, this has length 1.", 
            "dur": "5.95", 
            "start": "87.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And this has length a.", 
            "dur": "1.89", 
            "start": "93.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I&#39;m going to scale\nup the triangle.", 
            "dur": "3.42", 
            "start": "95.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I scale it up, so now this has\nlength b, the big triangle has", 
            "dur": "4.4", 
            "start": "98.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "length b, then this has been\nscaled up as well, so that", 
            "dur": "3.62", 
            "start": "103.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "this has a length a times b.", 
            "dur": "2.35", 
            "start": "106.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You divide.", 
            "dur": "0.68", 
            "start": "109.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Same idea, but it&#39;s the\nreverse of that.", 
            "dur": "2.11", 
            "start": "109.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I took a bigger triangle, if\nthat has a length of b, and", 
            "dur": "4.45", 
            "start": "112.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the long edge here has a length\nof a, if I scale it", 
            "dur": "4.89", 
            "start": "116.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "down so now this has a length\nof 1, then this has been", 
            "dur": "3.78", 
            "start": "121.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "scaled down as well.", 
            "dur": "1.57", 
            "start": "125.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you scale it down so\nit has a length of", 
            "dur": "1.754", 
            "start": "126.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a divided by b.", 
            "dur": "2.936", 
            "start": "128.524"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you can divide by scaling\ntriangles as well.", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "131.46"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And there&#39;s one more\nthing you can do.", 
            "dur": "1.595", 
            "start": "134.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I draw a line here,\nthis is a.", 
            "dur": "3.295", 
            "start": "136.195"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I&#39;m going to add 1 to it.", 
            "dur": "2.16", 
            "start": "139.49"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s 1.", 
            "dur": "1.4", 
            "start": "141.65"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I&#39;m then going to draw\na semicircle.", 
            "dur": "2.79", 
            "start": "143.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And this length, here, is\nthe square root of a.", 
            "dur": "7.43", 
            "start": "145.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And that&#39;s all you can do.", 
            "dur": "1.48", 
            "start": "153.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That is it.", 
            "dur": "1.17", 
            "start": "154.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "With a ruler and a compass, you\ncan add, multiply, divide,", 
            "dur": "5.43", 
            "start": "155.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "subtract, workout square\nroots, and that is it.", 
            "dur": "4.9", 
            "start": "161.35"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That is all you can do.", 
            "dur": "1.12", 
            "start": "166.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The numbers you make using\nthose rules are called", 
            "dur": "2.57", 
            "start": "167.37"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "constructible all numbers.", 
            "dur": "1.63", 
            "start": "169.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So all those numbers are\njust repeated use", 
            "dur": "2.76", 
            "start": "171.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of those few rules.", 
            "dur": "1.41", 
            "start": "174.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If we had a circle--", 
            "dur": "2.08", 
            "start": "175.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "let&#39;s this make this easy.", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "177.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s say this circle\nhas a radius of 1.", 
            "dur": "4.12", 
            "start": "179.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The area of the circle is pi\ntimes the radius squared.", 
            "dur": "6.53", 
            "start": "183.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And the radius squared,\nthat&#39;s 1.", 
            "dur": "2.3", 
            "start": "190.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the area of the circle\nis just pi.", 
            "dur": "2.74", 
            "start": "192.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So I want a square with\nthe same area.", 
            "dur": "2.83", 
            "start": "195.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I want a square now that\nhas an area of pi.", 
            "dur": "3.42", 
            "start": "198.3"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you may be ahead of me here,\nbecause a square has an", 
            "dur": "2.68", 
            "start": "201.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "area of pi, the lengths of the\nsides are the square root of", 
            "dur": "6.18", 
            "start": "204.4"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "pi", 
            "dur": "1.25", 
            "start": "210.58"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now it&#39;s at the square\nroot of pi.", 
            "dur": "1.4", 
            "start": "211.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We can do square roots.", 
            "dur": "1.3", 
            "start": "213.23"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s allowed.", 
            "dur": "1.28", 
            "start": "214.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So there&#39;s nothing yet to say\nthat we can&#39;t do this.", 
            "dur": "3.64", 
            "start": "215.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So what&#39;s the problem?", 
            "dur": "1.38", 
            "start": "219.45"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well we know that pi\nis irrational.", 
            "dur": "2.78", 
            "start": "220.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Actually, that wasn&#39;t\neasy to work out.", 
            "dur": "2.25", 
            "start": "223.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We only worked that out\nquite recently.", 
            "dur": "1.71", 
            "start": "225.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "By quite recently I mean 1761.", 
            "dur": "2.58", 
            "start": "227.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But being irrational\nis not enough.", 
            "dur": "2.65", 
            "start": "230.15"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There are constructible numbers\nthat are irrational.", 
            "dur": "4.31", 
            "start": "232.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can make the square root\nof 2 quite easily.", 
            "dur": "3.55", 
            "start": "237.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you can make the square\nroot of the square root", 
            "dur": "2.23", 
            "start": "240.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of 2, and so on.", 
            "dur": "1.98", 
            "start": "242.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So being irrational is not\nenough to say that", 
            "dur": "3.01", 
            "start": "244.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "this can&#39;t be done.", 
            "dur": "0.92", 
            "start": "247.88"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If I&#39;m allowed to make this\na bit more general, if I&#39;m", 
            "dur": "2.165", 
            "start": "248.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "allowed to use other roots,\nlike cube roots, or fifth", 
            "dur": "4.125", 
            "start": "250.965"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "roots, or nth roots, if I&#39;m\nallowed to add those in as", 
            "dur": "3.13", 
            "start": "255.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "well, the numbers that you can\nmake using those rules are", 
            "dur": "2.98", 
            "start": "258.22"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "called algebraic numbers.", 
            "dur": "1.8", 
            "start": "261.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s just a bit more\ngeneral, same idea.", 
            "dur": "2.005", 
            "start": "263"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it turns out that they were\nable to prove that pi was", 
            "dur": "3.835", 
            "start": "265.005"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "not an algebraic number.", 
            "dur": "2.77", 
            "start": "268.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And if it&#39;s not an algebraic\nnumber, then it&#39;s definitely", 
            "dur": "3.7", 
            "start": "271.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "not a constructible number.", 
            "dur": "1.94", 
            "start": "275.31"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now this is what I like.", 
            "dur": "1.48", 
            "start": "277.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The word for a number that is\nnot algebraic is called a", 
            "dur": "4.18", 
            "start": "278.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "transcendental number, which\nis a fantastic word.", 
            "dur": "4.3", 
            "start": "282.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now to prove something is\ntranscendental is really hard.", 
            "dur": "4.21", 
            "start": "287.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, mathematicians had\nshown that transcendental", 
            "dur": "3.56", 
            "start": "291.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "numbers existed seven years\nbefore they even found an", 
            "dur": "4.08", 
            "start": "294.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "example of a transcendental\nnumber.", 
            "dur": "2.8", 
            "start": "299.06"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you have to imagine in those\nseven years, people were", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "301.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "saying to the mathematicians,\nshow me a transcendental", 
            "dur": "3.39", 
            "start": "304.24"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "number, come on, show me a\ntranscendental number.", 
            "dur": "2.82", 
            "start": "307.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But it was a really\nhard thing to do.", 
            "dur": "2.14", 
            "start": "310.45"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Eventually they found a\nfew examples of this.", 
            "dur": "3.55", 
            "start": "312.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But we still have to wait until\nwe were able to prove", 
            "dur": "3.18", 
            "start": "316.14"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that pi itself was\ntranscendental.", 
            "dur": "3.71", 
            "start": "319.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And then that was\ndone in 1882.", 
            "dur": "4.19", 
            "start": "323.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Once we&#39;ve shown that, we&#39;ve\nshown that pi is not", 
            "dur": "3.44", 
            "start": "327.22"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "constructible.", 
            "dur": "1.43", 
            "start": "330.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And that is a proof that you\ncannot square the circle.", 
            "dur": "4.88", 
            "start": "332.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY: Can you only not square\nthis circle given the", 
            "dur": "2.7", 
            "start": "336.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "parameters of these rules\nin this game?", 
            "dur": "2.2", 
            "start": "339.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Could a computer square\na circle?", 
            "dur": "2.67", 
            "start": "341.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "DR. .JAMES GRIME: You can make\na square with sides that have", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "344.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "length root pi.", 
            "dur": "3.16", 
            "start": "347.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Absolutely.", 
            "dur": "1.44", 
            "start": "350.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So to the modern day people,\nwith our tools of algebra--", 
            "dur": "5.3", 
            "start": "351.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "algebra is fantastic.", 
            "dur": "1.31", 
            "start": "357.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "People complain about algebra,\nand having to", 
            "dur": "2.16", 
            "start": "358.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "learn algebra at school.", 
            "dur": "1.79", 
            "start": "360.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But if we didn&#39;t have algebra,\nwe would be doing maths like", 
            "dur": "3.13", 
            "start": "362.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Ancient Greeks did maths.", 
            "dur": "2.24", 
            "start": "365.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I promise you, that would\nbe much, much worse.", 
            "dur": "3.24", 
            "start": "367.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Your textbooks would\nbe ridiculous.", 
            "dur": "3.14", 
            "start": "370.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They&#39;d be very wordy.", 
            "dur": "2.35", 
            "start": "374.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Algebra is an amazing, powerful\ntool in mathematics.", 
            "dur": "3.2", 
            "start": "376.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s not there to cause\nyou problems.", 
            "dur": "2.44", 
            "start": "379.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s there for a reason.", 
            "dur": "1.21", 
            "start": "382.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s brilliant.", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "383.29"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So this is easy to make a square\nwith the area of pi.", 
            "dur": "6.23", 
            "start": "384.75"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But using the Greek rules,\nstraight lines and circles,", 
            "dur": "5.07", 
            "start": "390.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it&#39;s impossible to do.", 
            "dur": "1.85", 
            "start": "396.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY: You say it&#39;s easy\nto make a square", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "397.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with the area of pi.", 
            "dur": "1.91", 
            "start": "400.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But because pi has this nature\nwhere the digits continue, and", 
            "dur": "4.91", 
            "start": "402.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we can&#39;t even get to the exact\nfigure, surely you can&#39;t make", 
            "dur": "3.355", 
            "start": "407.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a square that&#39;s exactly pi.", 
            "dur": "1.415", 
            "start": "410.455"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Because you don&#39;t even\nknow what pi is.", 
            "dur": "1.63", 
            "start": "411.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you can do it, can you?", 
            "dur": "1.55", 
            "start": "413.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "DR. .JAMES GRIME: You can do\nit and you&#39;re treading on", 
            "dur": "3.2", 
            "start": "415.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "something called Zeno&#39;s Paradox\nthere, which we&#39;re", 
            "dur": "4.2", 
            "start": "418.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "about to do next.", 
            "dur": "3.015", 
            "start": "422.45"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY: OK.", 
            "dur": "1.895", 
            "start": "425.465"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So for a second video in a row\nwe&#39;re going to tell people", 
            "dur": "3.17", 
            "start": "427.36"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they have to wait to\nfind out more?", 
            "dur": "2.061", 
            "start": "430.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "DR. .JAMES GRIME: If that&#39;s the\nway you want to play it,", 
            "dur": "1.919", 
            "start": "432.591"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Brady, that&#39;s your choice.", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "434.51"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This is Brady&#39;s decision.", 
            "dur": "1.9", 
            "start": "436.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "He&#39;s stringing you along here.", 
            "dur": "2.98", 
            "start": "438.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The representatives\nactually passed it", 
            "dur": "3.36", 
            "start": "441.41"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "unanimously, 67 to 0.", 
            "dur": "2.99", 
            "start": "444.77"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They passed it.", 
            "dur": "0.82", 
            "start": "447.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now this is the weird bit.", 
            "dur": "2.49", 
            "start": "448.58"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "On the same day that they\nwere passing the bill--", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "451.07"
        }
